##Variables: 
#  Make - character(Nominal) - It is stating the name of the company of a particular car.
# Model - character(Nominal) - This column is stating the name of the car that is being manufactured.
#  Price - integer(Continuous) - The Price column contains the selling price of all the vehicles that we have in the data.
#  Year - integer(Discrete) - The Year column states the year in which a particular car was manufactured.
#  Kilometer - integer(Discrete) - This column mentions the amount of distance a car has travelled in its lifetime.
#  Fuel.Type - character(categorical) - The Fuel.Type column states the sort of fuel a car is using(Petrol/Deisel/CNG).
#  Transmission - character(nominal) - This column states the type of transmission a car has : Manual/Automatic.
#  Location - character(nominal) - #The Location column states the city in which a car is purchased.
#  Color - character(nominal) - #It mentions the color of a particular car.
#  Owner - character(nominal) - #This column specifies whether the car is first-hand, second-hand, etc.
#  Seller.Type - character(nominal) - This column specifies the type of seller(Individual,Corporate,etc).
#  Engine - integer(continuous) - The engine column is specifying the engine power(CC) of each car.
#  Max.Power - integer(continuous) - This column represents the maximum power output of the engine in horsepower.
#  Max.Torque - integer(continous) - This column represents the torque output of the engine in Newton meters.
#  Drivetrain - character(nominal) - The Drivetrain column specifies the the type of system that a car using to connect its engine to the drive axles
#  Length - integer(continuous) - It specifies the length of a car.
#  Width - integer(continuous) - It specifies the width of a car.
#  Height - integer(continuous) - It specifies the height of a car.
#  Seating.Capactiy -integer(discrete) - This column states the number of seats in a car.
# Fuel.Tank.Capacity -integer(continuous) - It specifies the maximum fuel capacity of a car.

#Converting Transmission into binary column <- Changing 'manual' to 0 and 'automatic' to 1

car_data$Transmission <- str_replace(car_data$Transmission, 'Automatic', "1")

#Converting Fuel Type into Ordinal Encoder
car_data$Fuel.Type <- str_replace(car_data$Fuel.Type, 'Petrol', "0")

car_data$Fuel.Type <- as.numeric(car_data$Fuel.Type)

car_data$Owner <- str_replace(car_data$Owner, 'Second', "1")

## named numeric(0)
#Variance Inflation Factor measures how much the behavior of an independent variable is 
#influenced by its correlation with the other independent variables. It allows a quick measure of how much a variable is contributing to the standard error in the regression.
#Generally VIF greater than 5 suggests multicollinearity. 

#From the correlation and the heatmap of correlation we can clearly see that there exists
#some relationship among the independent variables.
#As there exists some relationship, we first created a model with all the independent variables 
#and have calculated the VIF of the model
#With backward selection we have removed the variable with the highest VIF(greater than 5) and we continue to iterate this
#step till all the variables left have a VIF less than 5.
#Here, the backward selection is done manually.



#Assumption 4 - Independence of Observations
dwtest(df.lm)
## 
##  Durbin-Watson test
## 
## data:  df.lm
## DW = 1.9642, p-value = 0.2149
## alternative hypothesis: true autocorrelation is greater than 0
#The Durbin-Watson test is a statistical test that is used to detect the presence of autocorrelation
#(or serial correlation) in the errors or residuals of a regression analysis.
#Autocorrelation occurs when the errors in a regression model are correlated with each
#other over time or across observations, violating the assumption of independence between errors.

#The test statistic ranges from 0 to 4, where a value of 2 indicates no autocorrelation, a value below 2 indicates positive autocorrelation, 
#and a value above 2 indicates negative autocorrelation.

#The null hypothesis of the Durbin-Watson test is that there is no autocorrelation in the residuals, 
#while the alternative hypothesis is that there is autocorrelation. 
#The test is commonly used in time series analysis and econometrics, and 
#it can be applied to both simple and multiple regression models.

#We can see that the DW value is close to 2 and the p-value is greater than 0.05.
# Hence, we fail to reject our null hypothesis. 
#Therefore, there is no multicollinearity proving that there is independence of observations

#The Shapiro-Wilk test is a statistical test used to determine whether a given 
#data sample comes from a normally distributed population. 
#The null hypothesis of the test is that the data are normally distributed. 
#The alternative hypothesis is that the data are not normally distributed.
#From,the graph we can observe that it is normally distributed.
#However,in Shapiro-Wilk Test, we reject null hypothesis i.e. it is not normally distributed
#So, we used Cooks Distance to find the influential outliers and we remove them.
#Again, performing shapiro-wilk test after removing those outliers we fail to reject null hypothesis
#Therefore, it is normally distributed.
